sentences: Lucy Elizabeth Dacus (born May 2, 1995) is an American singer-songwriter and producer.
Originally from Richmond, Virginia, Dacus attracted attention with her debut album No Burden (2016), which led to a deal with Matador Records.
Her second album, Historian, was released in 2018 to further critical acclaim.
Dacus's third studio album, Home Video, was released in 2021.
In addition to her solo work, Dacus is also known as a member of the supergroup boygenius (formed in 2018), alongside Phoebe Bridgers and Julien Baker.

After graduating from Maggie L. Walker Governor's School in 2013, she began studying film at Virginia Commonwealth University, but left to pre-emptively eliminate future issues with student debt and estrangement.
Dacus first performed in New York City in March 2015.
Her first single, "I Don't Wanna Be Funny Anymore," premiered in November 2015.
The album was originally released digitally on CD, and on vinyl via Richmond's EggHunt Records on February 26, 2016.
Dacus was then signed to Matador Records, who re-released the album on September 9, 2016.
In October 2016 she played the London Calling festival in Amsterdam, as a replacement for The Duke Spirit, who were forced to cancel.
Dacus's second album, entitled Historian, was released on March 2, 2018.
In 2018, Dacus, along with Phoebe Bridgers and Julien Baker, formed the group Boygenius.
They released three songs in August 2018 and subsequently announced an EP and tour.
The EP, titled boygenius, came out on October 26, 2018.
In 2021, Dacus announced her third album, titled Home Video, which was released on June 25.
On November 10, Dacus released her single "Thumbs Again", a re-release of her song "Thumbs" with additional instrumentation, alongside the announcement of 2022 US tour dates.
On February 2, 2022, Dacus released a single “Kissing Lessons”, which was accompanied by a music video.

She performed one of the album's singles "Hot & Heavy" on The Late Show with Stephen Colbert on April 13.
As of June 2021, she resides in Philadelphia.
To coincide with Valentine's Day 2019, Dacus released a cover of "La Vie en rose", the first in a planned series of songs commemorating major holidays.

After graduating from Maggie L. Walker Governor's School in 2013, she began studying film at Virginia Commonwealth University, but left to pre-emptively eliminate future issues with student debt and estrangement.

Her debut album, No Burden, was produced in Nashville by her hometown friends, Berklee College of Music graduate Collin Pastore and Oberlin Conservatory of Music graduate Jacob Blizard; it was recorded at the request of Blizard for a school project.
In the same year she performed at Lollapalooza, in Chicago's Grant Park and made her national television debut on CBS This Morning.
She recorded a Tiny Desk Concert for NPR the same weekend.
Historian, like No Burden, was recorded in Nashville, at Trace Horse Studio, in a similar collaborative effort by Lucy Dacus, Jacob Blizard, and Collin Pastore.
In 2021, Dacus announced her third album, titled Home Video, which was released on June 25.
